Project: ohffs — GitHub MCP Server
ohffs is a TypeScript/Node.js MCP server that connects Claude Code (VS Code) to GitHub, enabling a full issue → branch → merge → close workflow. The goal is to discuss tasks in Claude.ai, then push them to GitHub as issues and branches in one shot via Claude Code.
Stack

TypeScript / Node.js MCP server
GitHub Personal Access Token (PAT) authentication (upgrade to GitHub App later)
Published to npm and the MCP Registry (registry.modelcontextprotocol.io)

Branch naming convention
close-{issue-number}-{kebab-title-slug} (title truncated to ~5 words, no forward slashes)
Example: close-42-add-hero-section-to-homepage
PR convention

Title: Close #42 - Add hero section to homepage
Body always includes: Closes #42 (triggers GitHub native auto-close on merge to main)

Build Phases
Phase 1 — Core MCP server

Scaffold TypeScript MCP server
PAT auth via .env
Tools: create_issue, create_branch, list_issues, close_issue
Single issue + branch creation end to end

Phase 2 — Bulk creation

create_issues_from_list tool
Accepts a markdown task list, creates all issues + branches in one shot
Auto-generates branch names from issue number + title slug

Phase 3 — Claude.ai bridge

Define a standard markdown paste format to carry task lists from claude.ai into Claude Code
Slash command (e.g. /push-to-github) that reads the task list and triggers Phase 2

Phase 4 — Auto-close on merge

Embed Closes #42 in PR body automatically on branch/PR creation
GitHub natively closes the issue on merge — no webhook infrastructure needed

Phase 5 — GitHub Projects v2 (optional, later)

Add issues to a GitHub Project board on creation
Update status fields as work progresses
Requires GraphQL API

Publishing targets

npm (package name: ohffs)
MCP Registry (registry.modelcontextprotocol.io) using mcp-publisher CLI
mcp.so, smithery.ai, glama.ai/mcp, punkpeye/awesome-mcp-servers list

Pre-build checklist

 GitHub repo created (public, initialised with README, named ohffs)
 GitHub PAT generated with repo + project scopes, 90-day expiry
 .env file set up locally with PAT

Conventions

All tools should confirm before bulk-creating (safety first)
Source of truth for issue state is always GitHub, never local
Keep the MCP tool surface minimal — do one thing well per tool